{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"DeadLetter"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}]},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"overview","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Often the reason for this is that the message was sent to given actor while it was still alive,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"yet once it arrived the destination node (or mailbox) the actor had already terminated, leaving the message to be dropped."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Since such races can happen and point to problems in an actor based algorithm, such messages are not silently dropped,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"but rather logged, with as much information as available (e.g. about the sender or source location of the initiating tell),"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"such that when operating the system, bugs regarding undelivered messages can be spotted and fixed."}]},{"anchor":"Not-all-dead-letters-are-problems","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Not all dead letters are problems"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"No, some dead letters may happen in a perfectly healthy system and if one knows that a message could arrive"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"“too late” or be dropped for some other reason, one may mark it using the TODO: “dont log me as dead letter” protocol."}]},{"anchor":"Trivia","level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Trivia"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The term dead letters, or rather “dead letter office” originates from the postal system, where undeliverable"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"mail would be called such, and shipped to one specific place to deal with these letters."}]}]}],"s